[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, thank you.

44
00:02:11,303 --> 00:02:12,984
[SPEAKER_09]: All right, I'm not going to dance and sing now.

45
00:02:13,285 --> 00:02:14,085
[SPEAKER_09]: So, anyway.

46
00:02:16,808 --> 00:02:19,410
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

47
00:02:19,470 --> 00:02:23,213
[SPEAKER_09]: President Morrell and her fellow council members, thank you for having us tonight.

48
00:02:23,794 --> 00:02:26,155
[SPEAKER_09]: As you know, we're here for the water and sewer enterprise budget.

49
00:02:28,217 --> 00:02:30,098
[SPEAKER_09]: I'll just highlight a couple of things.

50
00:02:30,899 --> 00:02:40,845
[SPEAKER_09]: You'll see on the tally of positions at the table that there's a water supervisor position and another water quality controller position.

51
00:02:41,245 --> 00:02:44,267
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's probably the biggest change here in this budget.

52
00:02:44,847 --> 00:02:52,312
[SPEAKER_09]: It's a different funding source than the general fund and we managed to keep us within the, you know,

53
00:02:53,192 --> 00:02:59,214
[SPEAKER_09]: with a relatively small increase, but to get a couple of higher level positions in there.

54
00:02:59,474 --> 00:03:02,755
[SPEAKER_09]: There were other open positions in there that we rearranged to make these positions.

55
00:03:03,315 --> 00:03:12,438
[SPEAKER_09]: Now the reason that we did it is, Dan can go into detail as you'd like, but as we discussed a little bit during the general fund hearing,

56
00:03:13,358 --> 00:03:23,002
[SPEAKER_09]: The assets, the utility assets are, you know, a lot of them are nearing their end of life, including the water and sewer, most importantly, the water.

57
00:03:23,583 --> 00:03:33,747
[SPEAKER_09]: So, you know, we anticipate having to ramp up how we are replacing our water mains and also brakes.

58
00:03:34,127 --> 00:03:35,808
[SPEAKER_09]: So we're anticipating that happening.

59
00:03:37,949 --> 00:03:53,178
[SPEAKER_09]: That's something we're having an additional who can work with more than one crew hopefully in the long run is the direction we want to head as well as taking in more relay work in-house as well.

60
00:03:54,759 --> 00:04:05,425
[SPEAKER_09]: We've practiced a little bit recently on Union Street to get a relay, a new water pipe in the ground by in-house and I think it was pretty successful.

61
00:04:06,305 --> 00:04:07,405
[SPEAKER_09]: So we'd like to continue that.

62
00:04:07,526 --> 00:04:08,806
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's part of the strategy.

63
00:04:09,506 --> 00:04:14,128
[SPEAKER_09]: The other position, the water quality controller position is also new.

64
00:04:14,288 --> 00:04:28,432
[SPEAKER_09]: We have a water quality controller currently, but from the size of our system, the amount of testing that we have to do for water quality and new regulatory requirements coming down the pike, a system of this size should have two.

65
00:04:29,152 --> 00:04:31,033
[SPEAKER_09]: So that should help there.

66
00:04:32,533 --> 00:04:41,875
[SPEAKER_09]: And besides that, another change that you'll see, and one of the ways that we've been able to have this flexibility is taking in camera work in-house.

67
00:04:42,155 --> 00:04:45,735
[SPEAKER_09]: So the technology is such that it's more affordable now than it was just a few years ago.

68
00:04:46,415 --> 00:04:51,996
[SPEAKER_09]: So we're trying to take in the camera work instead of contracting it out.

69
00:04:52,397 --> 00:04:54,797
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's another piece that we changed.

70
00:04:55,517 --> 00:04:59,398
[SPEAKER_09]: But besides that, it's very similar to what we proposed last year.

71
00:05:00,258 --> 00:05:00,758
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you very much.

72
00:05:02,643 --> 00:05:03,343
[SPEAKER_08]: Questions from the council?

73
00:05:04,304 --> 00:05:04,924
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Carvalho.

74
00:05:07,105 --> 00:05:07,846
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you, Madam President.

75
00:05:09,446 --> 00:05:13,248
[SPEAKER_12]: Tim, how far along are we in the meter project?

76
00:05:15,289 --> 00:05:20,291
[SPEAKER_09]: We just recently awarded the contractor who's going to be doing the work.

77
00:05:20,472 --> 00:05:24,233
[SPEAKER_09]: So we've purchased the meters and now we- We haven't actually started them yet.

78
00:05:24,934 --> 00:05:26,715
[SPEAKER_09]: Well, we started it because we have the meters.

79
00:05:26,735 --> 00:05:31,457
[SPEAKER_09]: So in-house, we've started replacing the bad ones, but I don't know if we have a start date for the contractor yet.

80
00:05:35,572 --> 00:05:40,896
[SPEAKER_12]: What projects do you have coming up that we intend on using the Water and Sewer Enterprise Fund for?

81
00:05:42,457 --> 00:05:47,920
[SPEAKER_09]: We have some equipment purchases that we'd like to make with retained earnings.

82
00:05:48,841 --> 00:05:59,408
[SPEAKER_09]: And then right now we have some MWA loans and we're paying debt service on, I think, six water main replacements, including Union, Guild,

83
00:06:01,269 --> 00:06:10,095
[SPEAKER_09]: Brookings, Vista, and then so the Water and Sewer Enterprise Fund would pay the debt service for those.

84
00:06:11,076 --> 00:06:16,859
[SPEAKER_09]: And then the next round of streets, I believe, would be, we try to get on retained earnings.

85
00:06:18,140 --> 00:06:19,321
[SPEAKER_09]: But plenty of work to do.

86
00:06:20,402 --> 00:06:24,985
[SPEAKER_12]: I was reading your report today from the MWRA and saying that we're not up to stuff on some stuff.

87
00:06:25,725 --> 00:06:27,966
[SPEAKER_12]: Do you want to comment on that, on some testing?

88
00:06:29,741 --> 00:06:30,021
[SPEAKER_09]: Sure.

89
00:06:31,002 --> 00:06:34,364
[SPEAKER_09]: Maybe, Dan, you want to feel that a little bit?

90
00:06:35,564 --> 00:06:45,570
[SPEAKER_11]: So the violations that we've received recently were for lead and copper, and they were just for basically filing and paperwork.

91
00:06:45,950 --> 00:06:50,712
[SPEAKER_11]: It wasn't anything to do with quality or the safety of the water in any way.

92
00:06:52,469 --> 00:06:58,874
[SPEAKER_11]: We do also on our consumer confidence report have an E. coli positive.

93
00:07:00,175 --> 00:07:03,918
[SPEAKER_11]: This happened, we believe, due to an error at the lab.

94
00:07:04,418 --> 00:07:08,602
[SPEAKER_11]: So we retested and there was no confirmed E. coli.

95
00:07:09,022 --> 00:07:14,246
[SPEAKER_11]: But unfortunately, we have to put that in the consumer confidence report.

96
00:07:15,927 --> 00:07:19,610
[SPEAKER_11]: But unfortunately, we have to put that in the consumer confidence report.

97
00:07:20,231 --> 00:07:21,832
[SPEAKER_12]: Are we flushing our pipes on a regular basis?

98
00:07:22,429 --> 00:07:27,333
[SPEAKER_11]: We are not, we currently have Western Sampson working on a unidirectional flushing program.

99
00:07:28,714 --> 00:07:33,737
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't think the city of Medford has flushed very much at all in the past 30 years.

100
00:07:34,338 --> 00:07:39,401
[SPEAKER_11]: So that's caused a lot of concerns, but we have a program that's starting up.

101
00:07:40,522 --> 00:07:42,644
[SPEAKER_11]: Whether it's successful, we'll find out.

102
00:07:42,664 --> 00:07:45,166
[SPEAKER_12]: What's the cost of that program?

103
00:07:45,426 --> 00:07:50,149
[SPEAKER_11]: So I believe it's going to be roughly, it's a very rough number, 130,000.

104
00:07:52,230 --> 00:07:54,442
[SPEAKER_12]: Is that going to come out of the water and sort of retain your news accounts?

105
00:07:55,748 --> 00:08:00,130
[SPEAKER_11]: No, I believe we're budgeted this year, 40,000, and next year, 40,000.

106
00:08:00,170 --> 00:08:04,852
[SPEAKER_11]: So we just have to- Well, we may need to come back or retain earnings.

107
00:08:05,673 --> 00:08:15,097
[SPEAKER_09]: One of the things that we're going to find out as we get the fleshing program going again is how much more we need to do, how bad it is, how much money we should be spending each year.

108
00:08:15,477 --> 00:08:19,339
[SPEAKER_09]: So as Dan mentioned, we have about $140,000 planned over the next couple of years, but it may need to be more.

109
00:08:23,621 --> 00:08:25,882
[SPEAKER_09]: and I don't think we have that entirely funded.

110
00:08:26,303 --> 00:08:31,086
[SPEAKER_09]: I know we have, it's partially funded, so we may be coming to you for retained earnings for that as well.

111
00:08:32,287 --> 00:08:36,550
[SPEAKER_09]: That's going to be something that we have to do, we should be doing every single year.

112
00:08:36,570 --> 00:08:40,113
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay, that's it for me at the moment.

113
00:08:42,195 --> 00:08:43,276
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Vice President Behrs.

114
00:08:44,056 --> 00:08:44,777
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Madam President.

115
00:08:46,358 --> 00:08:48,980
[SPEAKER_17]: Could you guys describe just the general condition of the system

116
00:08:49,733 --> 00:08:54,874
[SPEAKER_17]: it's age, it's need, any risks that are within that, et cetera?

117
00:08:55,475 --> 00:09:04,697
[SPEAKER_09]: Sure, yep, and I'll also refer, I'll speak about it a little bit, and also there's an asset management report that's available on the engineering website that gives some detail.

118
00:09:05,737 --> 00:09:12,239
[SPEAKER_09]: But the system itself, and Dan, please chime in, the system itself was mostly installed in the early 1900s, the 10s, the 20s, and the 30s.

119
00:09:16,680 --> 00:09:22,223
[SPEAKER_09]: The type of pipe they use has a life cycle from 100 to 150 years, more or less.

120
00:09:23,103 --> 00:09:31,227
[SPEAKER_09]: So, you know, we're entering that phase where, you know, the majority of the pipes installed in our city are coming of age.

121
00:09:32,047 --> 00:09:39,053
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's not just the pipes, but that's also the valves, that's also the hydrants, that's also service lines in a lot of cases.

122
00:09:40,275 --> 00:09:48,302
[SPEAKER_09]: So, you know, one of the things that we've made a considerable amount of progress on is service lines, and that's part of the getting the lead out initiative.

123
00:09:48,962 --> 00:09:58,671
[SPEAKER_09]: But what we are still in need of ramping up, which hence the strategy, you know, I think we're going to try to ramping up over the next quite a number of years,

124
00:09:59,311 --> 00:10:09,056
[SPEAKER_09]: is to get the older pipes, mostly the six inch cast iron pipes out of the ground and getting modern eight inch ductile iron in the ground.

125
00:10:10,057 --> 00:10:13,599
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's a focus of us, that's a focus of the MWRA as well.

126
00:10:14,689 --> 00:10:22,755
[SPEAKER_17]: Great, yeah, that leads right into my next question, which is, what does that long-term strategic plan look like, especially in terms of costs and rates?

127
00:10:23,196 --> 00:10:25,337
[SPEAKER_09]: Sure, so that's a great question.

128
00:10:25,357 --> 00:10:30,622
[SPEAKER_09]: And one of the things that we're working with the mayor on doing is a long-term rate study.

129
00:10:30,902 --> 00:10:31,742
[SPEAKER_09]: So it hasn't started yet.

130
00:10:32,523 --> 00:10:36,646
[SPEAKER_09]: So this is going to be something that is very much needed.

131
00:10:36,666 --> 00:10:38,328
[SPEAKER_09]: Other municipalities do it.

132
00:10:38,828 --> 00:10:42,251
[SPEAKER_09]: So it matches any rate increases

133
00:10:42,911 --> 00:11:00,495
[SPEAKER_09]: with funding in the enterprise fund for a strategy such as this, knowing that over the next 10 years plus, our system is going to be, you know, experiencing more breaks and is going to be experiencing less performance.

134
00:11:00,955 --> 00:11:12,578
[SPEAKER_09]: So, you know, we're really looking to make sure that our revenue matches up with the work that we need to do and that that work is going to be both contracted work and in-house work.

135
00:11:13,859 --> 00:11:14,539
[SPEAKER_17]: Great.

136
00:11:15,519 --> 00:11:18,421
[SPEAKER_17]: This one, feel free to answer however best you can.

137
00:11:20,402 --> 00:11:29,806
[SPEAKER_17]: It seems to me that it would be fair to say that the strategy for a long time has not been kind of comprehensive, looking at the whole system and what it's going to take to bring it up to modern standards.

138
00:11:29,826 --> 00:11:31,747
[SPEAKER_17]: It seems that that's now changing.

139
00:11:31,767 --> 00:11:41,391
[SPEAKER_17]: But one piece of that has been using, you know, basically we've been taking money from the surplus and reserves that are what we call retained earnings, which is really just the reserves for this enterprise fund.

140
00:11:42,277 --> 00:11:48,879
[SPEAKER_17]: every year to reduce rates versus maybe using that to invest in the system and bringing it up to par?

141
00:11:48,999 --> 00:12:02,584
[SPEAKER_17]: Is that a fair statement that maybe we're shifting to a different strategy from just not trying to comprehensively repair the system and keeping rates low with reserves to using all of the money that we collect to make sure that the system is brought up to where it needs to be?

142
00:12:03,555 --> 00:12:05,856
[SPEAKER_09]: I think that's a fair statement.

143
00:12:05,896 --> 00:12:08,937
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't want to look backwards and criticize.

144
00:12:08,977 --> 00:12:10,598
[SPEAKER_09]: I'd like to look forward and plan.

145
00:12:11,698 --> 00:12:20,182
[SPEAKER_09]: With that said, when I took the leadership of the DPW, one of the things that I noticed was,

146
00:12:21,662 --> 00:12:23,683
[SPEAKER_09]: a need for some long-term planning here.

147
00:12:23,703 --> 00:12:44,271
[SPEAKER_09]: And that's partially because I was city engineer before this, and we commissioned the asset management evaluation a few years ago, which basically told us where the risky places are, where the most critical pipes are, depending on what they service, and what the age of those pipes are.

148
00:12:44,391 --> 00:12:46,252
[SPEAKER_09]: And it basically overlays all that information.

149
00:12:46,912 --> 00:12:50,214
[SPEAKER_09]: and gives us a breakdown of what we need to do.

150
00:12:50,614 --> 00:13:13,806
[SPEAKER_09]: And one of the first things was to replace the six-inch cast iron unlined lines, which is what that, last year we began with a round of the most dire, six streets, and then we'll just, the plan is to then have another round of six or seven or eight streets to keep the ball rolling until we get it all out of the ground, which

151
00:13:14,706 --> 00:13:19,347
[SPEAKER_09]: We'll take some time, which is why we both need an in-house effort and a contracted effort.

152
00:13:19,947 --> 00:13:20,107
[SPEAKER_17]: Great.

153
00:13:20,127 --> 00:13:35,610
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, and I understand how my framing could seem critical of the past, but it was more so that residents can start to understand that there may be a change in how much rates go up every year because we're moving from kind of a status quo strategy to a strategy where we're fixing the system.

154
00:13:36,430 --> 00:13:42,391
[SPEAKER_17]: And whether that's taken as a criticism of the past or not, I just think it's important for residents to understand that things may feel a little bit different.

155
00:13:43,207 --> 00:13:45,010
[SPEAKER_09]: It's right to plan to move forward right now.

156
00:13:45,170 --> 00:13:46,992
[SPEAKER_09]: So, you know, and we're not alone.

157
00:13:47,412 --> 00:13:57,204
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, like I was saying other municipalities have done this somewhat recently where you have to say, Okay, well you know I'm our city had a boom of water pipe building in the 20s and 30s.

158
00:13:58,185 --> 00:14:07,168
[SPEAKER_09]: And we're getting to a point where those pipes are, you know, a lot of them aren't even passing the flow that we would like to see out of them.

159
00:14:07,329 --> 00:14:15,692
[SPEAKER_09]: So it really comes down to the time is ripe to do some long term planning with our revenue for the enterprise fund.

160
00:14:16,172 --> 00:14:16,952
[SPEAKER_17]: Great.

161
00:14:17,612 --> 00:14:18,753
[SPEAKER_17]: And just last question.

162
00:14:19,394 --> 00:14:28,353
[SPEAKER_17]: This is all in the service of avoiding what you would call what a catastrophic event or do you have a word phrase for it that I can't remember an incident where there's like a water main break or something like that.

163
00:14:29,452 --> 00:14:42,603
[SPEAKER_09]: Hopefully it's not catastrophic, but the idea would be to, you know, as we replace the pipes that are the oldest and have seen the most breaks, it will reduce the rate of breaks that we see over time.

164
00:14:43,303 --> 00:14:51,190
[SPEAKER_09]: And it will also, over time, increase the flows and pressures in our system, and it will also increase the water quality of our system.

165
00:14:52,130 --> 00:14:55,633
[SPEAKER_09]: And, you know, we're talking about water here, so, you know, this is all very important.

166
00:15:00,245 --> 00:15:04,070
[SPEAKER_09]: know, that won't last forever if you just leave the same pipes in the ground.

167
00:15:04,270 --> 00:15:10,678
[SPEAKER_09]: So at some point, you know, within the next 10 or 20 years, it's going to reach that point of no return.

168
00:15:11,038 --> 00:15:15,464
[SPEAKER_09]: And we are working on a strategy so we don't reach that point of no return.

169
00:15:15,888 --> 00:15:22,249
[SPEAKER_17]: Great, may not be something everybody sees every day, but it's something everybody uses, and it's really important, and I'm glad to hear that we're taking this approach.

170
00:15:22,629 --> 00:15:34,371
[SPEAKER_09]: Absolutely, yeah, I think, you know, with Dan leading the Water and Sewer Division, and myself now leading the department, we're committed to, you know, planning this out the best way we can.

171
00:15:35,032 --> 00:15:36,492
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's what we intend to do.

172
00:15:37,192 --> 00:15:38,392
[SPEAKER_17]: Great, thank you, thank you both.

173
00:15:38,412 --> 00:15:41,133
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Councilor Carvalho.

174
00:15:41,153 --> 00:15:42,593
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you, Tim, a couple more questions.

175
00:15:44,558 --> 00:15:50,563
