360
00:29:05,922 --> 00:29:08,824
[SPEAKER_06]: I did a calculation if we hadn't cut in 2019 which

361
00:29:10,552 --> 00:29:18,659
[SPEAKER_06]: If I could go back in time, we wouldn't cut in 2019, but we would be at about 519,000 if we'd gone up 2.5% every year.

362
00:29:19,259 --> 00:29:23,503
[SPEAKER_06]: So 383 is, it's below FY17.

363
00:29:23,563 --> 00:29:30,509
[SPEAKER_06]: It's above FY16, which is better than last year, but it is gonna be a struggle this year to do all the stuff that we need to do.

364
00:29:30,529 --> 00:29:34,392
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that was everything I was gonna say, yes.

365
00:29:35,513 --> 00:29:36,514
[SPEAKER_08]: Great, thank you.

366
00:29:36,754 --> 00:29:37,735
[SPEAKER_08]: We'll go to Vice President Behrs.

367
00:29:38,723 --> 00:29:40,043
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Madam President.

368
00:29:40,063 --> 00:29:40,764
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Barbara.

369
00:29:42,704 --> 00:29:45,785
[SPEAKER_17]: You answered my first question, which was just talking about all the programming and services.

370
00:29:45,825 --> 00:29:48,806
[SPEAKER_17]: I think it's so important for people to hear everything that happens in this building.

371
00:29:48,826 --> 00:29:52,507
[SPEAKER_17]: I think it's fair to say we built it, and the people are coming, and they're a lot.

372
00:29:52,647 --> 00:29:55,908
[SPEAKER_17]: They're just there all the time, and we're doing a lot of stuff, and it's really exciting.

373
00:29:55,928 --> 00:30:01,210
[SPEAKER_17]: And it's just a wonderful place, wonderful place here in Medford to have.

374
00:30:02,962 --> 00:30:19,006
[SPEAKER_17]: My other question you got into a little bit, which is just that if the library hadn't gone down to the smaller budget for the temporary space, and if it had been increased every year, it would be significantly higher on the ordinary expense, the non-personnel expense budget than it is now.

375
00:30:19,946 --> 00:30:24,047
[SPEAKER_17]: What's the impact of not having those resources

376
00:30:26,337 --> 00:30:28,378
[SPEAKER_17]: on the people who go to library.

377
00:30:28,758 --> 00:30:32,380
[SPEAKER_06]: My original, my budget request was 87,000 higher than this.

378
00:30:32,880 --> 00:30:34,501
[SPEAKER_06]: That covered the basics.

379
00:30:35,562 --> 00:30:42,325
[SPEAKER_06]: We always expect to have to use a little bit of state aid to make up the difference, because we've never actually been fully funded in my memory.

380
00:30:42,685 --> 00:30:52,870
[SPEAKER_06]: But where this is probably going to make an impact this year is with the eBooks, because the way it works, the Minuteman network buys copies.

381
00:30:54,482 --> 00:30:59,265
[SPEAKER_06]: And then everybody in the network could just wait for those copies, which is months.

382
00:30:59,345 --> 00:31:01,107
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, six months, nine months.

383
00:31:01,747 --> 00:31:04,349
[SPEAKER_06]: Instead, we buy our own copies.

384
00:31:04,629 --> 00:31:08,532
[SPEAKER_06]: It's what we do with books too, so that Medford people don't have to wait as long.

385
00:31:08,992 --> 00:31:10,593
[SPEAKER_06]: We're not going to be able to do as much of that.

386
00:31:10,713 --> 00:31:15,317
[SPEAKER_06]: And we're not going to be able to do as much of that with books either, if there isn't some kind of an increase.

387
00:31:17,955 --> 00:31:30,047
[SPEAKER_06]: I know in the terms of world events, it doesn't seem like a terrible thing, but that's a very basic level of service that we should be funded for, just the ability to provide people with the thing that a library does the most.

388
00:31:30,067 --> 00:31:31,228
[SPEAKER_17]: The library should have books.

389
00:31:31,608 --> 00:31:32,569
[SPEAKER_06]: Library should have books.

390
00:31:33,170 --> 00:31:34,951
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

391
00:31:35,011 --> 00:31:37,394
[SPEAKER_06]: Just kind of basically, and all of the other stuff.

392
00:31:41,733 --> 00:31:42,294
[SPEAKER_17]: Thanks, thanks.

393
00:31:42,615 --> 00:31:51,171
[SPEAKER_17]: That's helpful and it sounds like the ebook program is really successful it's where we're actually outpacing what we usually do that we have, we have to ebook platforms do we have one called hoopla that.

394
00:31:52,355 --> 00:31:55,936
[SPEAKER_06]: is also, which is, I think is just for Metro people, and that's at 16,000.

395
00:31:56,276 --> 00:32:01,757
[SPEAKER_06]: And that also has movies, audio, they all have audio books and eBooks.

396
00:32:02,357 --> 00:32:03,237
[SPEAKER_06]: Hoopla has movies.

397
00:32:04,117 --> 00:32:20,140
[SPEAKER_06]: We have a film streaming service called Canopy that also is very popular because it's like eBooks didn't take over the world, but the availability of more formats has made it possible for people to read books, watch movies in different ways.

398
00:32:21,343 --> 00:32:23,745
[SPEAKER_06]: It's all part of books.

399
00:32:23,825 --> 00:32:27,307
[SPEAKER_06]: It's all part of what we offer as our basic, it's what we do.

400
00:32:27,948 --> 00:32:31,870
[SPEAKER_06]: We do a lot of other stuff, but that's where libraries came from.

401
00:32:32,911 --> 00:32:34,112
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah.

402
00:32:34,292 --> 00:32:41,557
[SPEAKER_17]: My only other question, because I definitely think we need to work on that by next Tuesday.

403
00:32:41,577 --> 00:32:43,679
[SPEAKER_06]: I would appreciate that.

404
00:32:44,579 --> 00:32:46,801
[SPEAKER_17]: What would it take for the library to be open on Sundays?

405
00:32:50,123 --> 00:32:50,746
[SPEAKER_06]: Couldn't be this year.

406
00:32:51,148 --> 00:32:52,132
[SPEAKER_06]: Not this year, yeah.

407
00:32:52,534 --> 00:32:54,904
[SPEAKER_17]: Just in the grand scope, I think that's a good goal.

408
00:32:55,239 --> 00:33:04,801
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, it's because that is we know that's what something I meant to mention is we did a strategic plan this year and our staffing levels are significantly lower than everybody.

409
00:33:05,001 --> 00:33:14,544
[SPEAKER_06]: People who are people, libraries that are the same size, have 30 full time staff and probably another 20, 25, 30 part time staff.

410
00:33:14,824 --> 00:33:16,124
[SPEAKER_06]: We have 30 people total.

411
00:33:16,504 --> 00:33:22,065
[SPEAKER_06]: I have 17 full time because we lost again in the 2000s, lost a lot of full time positions.

412
00:33:22,725 --> 00:33:24,966
[SPEAKER_06]: The thing with Saturdays, Sundays is that

413
00:33:26,006 --> 00:33:31,329
[SPEAKER_06]: It is not part of the work week, the regular work week that's defined by the contract.

414
00:33:31,730 --> 00:33:32,850
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a separate staff.

415
00:33:33,691 --> 00:33:43,956
[SPEAKER_06]: So when we figured out the logistics of it, it can be regular staff who want to work, who want to volunteer, and they get $3 more an hour.

416
00:33:44,497 --> 00:33:47,879
[SPEAKER_06]: Or it could be a separate Sunday staff, which is the most likely thing.

417
00:33:48,819 --> 00:33:58,726
[SPEAKER_06]: The wild card is that if it's the people who vote and you can't say no you can't volunteer so if all of the most highly paid people work Sundays it could be as much as an additional $60,000.

418
00:33:59,366 --> 00:34:00,647
[SPEAKER_06]: It's probably closer to 40.

419
00:34:01,607 --> 00:34:02,088
[SPEAKER_06]: It depends.

420
00:34:04,449 --> 00:34:06,711
[SPEAKER_06]: The thing is that's, you know, that's a nice thing.

421
00:34:08,052 --> 00:34:10,473
[SPEAKER_06]: we don't have enough people for the middle of the week.

422
00:34:10,833 --> 00:34:18,637
[SPEAKER_06]: At this point, I can't guarantee that Children's is not gonna get closed every now and then because all it takes is two people with the flu to wipe out the daily schedule.

423
00:34:18,717 --> 00:34:30,003
[SPEAKER_06]: So I wanna get us to Sunday hours, but I wanna make our regular staffing more stable before we start adding other stuff.

424
00:34:31,363 --> 00:34:33,865
[SPEAKER_06]: Because the optics on Sunday hours is great.

425
00:34:33,885 --> 00:34:36,086
[SPEAKER_06]: It looks like this new thing we're adding, but it doesn't,

426
00:34:37,662 --> 00:34:48,270
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't want it to take away from the fact that, you know, we have 700 people a day coming through and we need to serve the days in the week, which are more populated.

427
00:34:49,050 --> 00:34:50,491
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, no, and that's helpful.

428
00:34:50,812 --> 00:34:54,794
[SPEAKER_17]: I appreciate the comprehensive answer, because what would it take isn't just how much would it cost to do Sunday.

429
00:34:54,854 --> 00:34:56,996
[SPEAKER_17]: It's, yeah, is that the first thing we should do?

430
00:34:57,696 --> 00:34:58,057
[SPEAKER_06]: Exactly.

431
00:34:58,097 --> 00:35:03,741
[SPEAKER_06]: And I would say no, I know that people would like that, but it would only be a four, it would be a four hour day, but just wouldn't be.

432
00:35:05,683 --> 00:35:07,583
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, we don't have, we just, we just.

433
00:35:08,463 --> 00:35:08,684
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

434
00:35:10,984 --> 00:35:14,865
[SPEAKER_06]: Ideal situation in a business is one person does one job.

435
00:35:15,845 --> 00:35:18,405
[SPEAKER_06]: No one at the Metropolitan Library just does one job.

436
00:35:18,465 --> 00:35:23,666
[SPEAKER_06]: Everybody does all or most of what was once another full-time job.

437
00:35:23,766 --> 00:35:25,766
[SPEAKER_06]: Some people are doing, Sam is doing like 11.

438
00:35:26,206 --> 00:35:28,107
[SPEAKER_06]: I think I'm down to three, which is nice.

439
00:35:28,167 --> 00:35:33,848
[SPEAKER_06]: And it just, we make it work and we do a good job, but we need some more people.

440
00:35:35,977 --> 00:35:45,743
[SPEAKER_06]: we need to have the opportunity to sit down and do some long range planning for, you know, we wanna get this position and we need this position and how can we do that over five years?

441
00:35:45,783 --> 00:35:48,984
[SPEAKER_06]: That's not something I have ever had the opportunity to do.

442
00:35:49,725 --> 00:35:54,568
[SPEAKER_06]: And we're gonna do it in-house this year, but I would very much like to be able to have that conversation with the administration.

443
00:35:57,129 --> 00:35:58,330
[SPEAKER_06]: Cause I know how to do math now.

444
00:36:00,327 --> 00:36:01,888
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, building the library taught you math.

445
00:36:01,928 --> 00:36:02,788
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, I learned how to do math.

446
00:36:02,828 --> 00:36:03,908
[SPEAKER_06]: Payroll taught me math.

447
00:36:04,048 --> 00:36:04,909
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah.

448
00:36:05,049 --> 00:36:05,829
[SPEAKER_17]: Those are my only questions.

449
00:36:05,849 --> 00:36:08,990
[SPEAKER_17]: I'll just finish and say exactly, you just talked about long-term planning.

450
00:36:09,430 --> 00:36:11,271
[SPEAKER_17]: Water and sewer just talked about long-term planning.

451
00:36:11,771 --> 00:36:16,192
[SPEAKER_17]: All of the departments we've talked to pretty much in the past two and a half weeks have talked about long-term planning.

452
00:36:16,672 --> 00:36:21,094
[SPEAKER_17]: This council has been talking about long-term planning for at least the four years I've been on it.

453
00:36:21,114 --> 00:36:23,255
[SPEAKER_17]: It sounds like we need to do some long-term planning.

454
00:36:23,695 --> 00:36:24,495
[SPEAKER_08]: It would be useful.

455
00:36:24,795 --> 00:36:25,155
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

456
00:36:25,956 --> 00:36:26,616
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Carvillo.

457
00:36:28,396 --> 00:36:29,097
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you, Madam President.

458
00:36:31,604 --> 00:36:35,348
[SPEAKER_12]: You have probably the most popular building in the area here.

459
00:36:35,408 --> 00:36:36,069
[SPEAKER_06]: I think so.

460
00:36:36,129 --> 00:36:38,231
[SPEAKER_12]: The numbers are astounding.

461
00:36:39,032 --> 00:36:44,658
[SPEAKER_12]: And again, we're doing it with smoke and mirrors again.

462
00:36:45,919 --> 00:36:48,342
[SPEAKER_12]: And you know what the part that slays me the most is

463
00:36:50,122 --> 00:36:58,708
[SPEAKER_12]: We have a state-of-the-art library in Medford that we literally own for 50 cents on the dollar.

464
00:36:59,068 --> 00:37:01,230
[SPEAKER_12]: We have that library for half price.

465
00:37:01,850 --> 00:37:02,771
[SPEAKER_06]: Less than half price.

466
00:37:02,911 --> 00:37:03,812
[SPEAKER_12]: Less than half price.

467
00:37:04,932 --> 00:37:10,276
[SPEAKER_12]: And why we cannot fund it properly is beyond me, beyond me.

468
00:37:10,637 --> 00:37:17,782
[SPEAKER_12]: Imagine if we were paying a note on 27 million or 28 million dollars that other cities are paying.

469
00:37:18,925 --> 00:37:20,285
[SPEAKER_12]: the library would probably be shut down.

470
00:37:21,045 --> 00:37:31,587
[SPEAKER_12]: So the city is saving a ton of money and to underfund it to the level that you're saying, I mean, we are the second lowest funded library in the greater Boston area.

471
00:37:32,947 --> 00:37:36,228
[SPEAKER_12]: And we have probably the newest and the best library in the greater Boston area.

472
00:37:36,688 --> 00:37:47,550
[SPEAKER_12]: And it's literally an embarrassment to sit here after two years and be begging for money to keep a library open that shouldn't be asking for money.

473
00:37:48,885 --> 00:37:56,607
[SPEAKER_12]: I mean, we have a foundation that's been helpful, but how often can you keep going to the well of the foundation and the donors?

474
00:37:56,647 --> 00:38:02,668
[SPEAKER_12]: And I know some of the donors are being turned off because they feel the city's not making the right commitments.

475
00:38:03,649 --> 00:38:04,369
[SPEAKER_12]: And they're right.

476
00:38:04,809 --> 00:38:05,129
[SPEAKER_12]: They're right.

477
00:38:05,309 --> 00:38:12,071
[SPEAKER_12]: And the staff has been doing as much as they can to keep on raising funds and raising funds.

478
00:38:14,450 --> 00:38:18,353
[SPEAKER_12]: At what point does the city step up and pay their fair share?

479
00:38:19,114 --> 00:38:22,296
[SPEAKER_12]: You can't expect donors to pay for our library.

480
00:38:23,898 --> 00:38:25,379
[SPEAKER_12]: That's really the bottom line.

481
00:38:25,579 --> 00:38:31,704
[SPEAKER_12]: Again, we own the library for 45 to 50 cents on a dollar and shame on us for not being able to fund it.

482
00:38:35,027 --> 00:38:35,327
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

483
00:38:35,587 --> 00:38:36,828
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Councilor Collins.

484
00:38:39,247 --> 00:38:39,928
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, President Morrell.

485
00:38:39,968 --> 00:38:42,529
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you so much for being here today, Director Kerr.

486
00:38:43,330 --> 00:38:47,472
[SPEAKER_04]: It's always great to hear about all the wonderful things that the library is doing.

487
00:38:47,532 --> 00:38:56,378
[SPEAKER_04]: It's really quite moving, especially since in this building, it's only been open for such a short time and already constituents are flocking to it.

488
00:38:56,438 --> 00:39:02,202
[SPEAKER_04]: These statistics are really, they demonstrate to me like all of the pent-up demand for this kind of community space in the city.

489
00:39:03,663 --> 00:39:11,753
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, demand that was there before it opened its doors all the needs that are being addressed in the library and all the resources that it has it's really beautiful to hear about.

490
00:39:11,773 --> 00:39:19,863
[SPEAKER_04]: I think you could easily make the argument that it's probably the most helpful public building in the city, you know, virtually in person.

491
00:39:23,047 --> 00:39:42,366
[SPEAKER_04]: In light of that, it's really not clear to me how we can build a library to really be a 21st century library for a city of 60,000 people and fund it like we're a small community where there's not a lot of kids, not a lot of need, not a lot of teens, not a lot of families, or not a lot of community groups.

492
00:39:42,939 --> 00:39:46,121
[SPEAKER_04]: Like, because that's us and that's what people are already using the library for.

493
00:39:47,481 --> 00:40:01,728
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, hearing about even something like you said, something so simple as do we have the funding to purchase enough eBooks and books that people can just get them from our library instead of, you know, I think everybody's had that experience where you request a book and it's like, oh, it's coming from Needham.

494
00:40:02,208 --> 00:40:04,089
[SPEAKER_04]: All right, I'll wait another week or whatever.

495
00:40:04,749 --> 00:40:10,272
[SPEAKER_04]: But you make the right point, which is we have libraries that we can provide services here.

496
00:40:11,183 --> 00:40:16,593
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think what is upsetting is that I think we see a pattern of this in our community.

497
00:40:17,266 --> 00:40:28,952
[SPEAKER_04]: when we don't act quickly enough to reverse this chronic underfunding is these basic constituent services get foisted off onto other municipalities or nonprofits or NGOs.

498
00:40:29,932 --> 00:40:40,298
[SPEAKER_04]: And the result is this unreliable or inconvenient access for our own residents, which I think you guys are doing an incredible job with the resources that you do have.

499
00:40:41,198 --> 00:40:45,520
[SPEAKER_04]: But it's just too important to not start reversing that course as quickly as we can.

500
00:40:48,104 --> 00:41:00,614
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, so I know the library only opened, was it around this time last year I don't remember what month it was, you know, and I know that budgetarily we've been in, you know, a hard condition for several budget cycles now.

501
00:41:01,415 --> 00:41:04,797
[SPEAKER_04]: But, you know, we're responsible for funding the city that we do have.

502
00:41:06,078 --> 00:41:07,439
[SPEAKER_04]: We have the state-of-the-art library.

503
00:41:08,099 --> 00:41:18,705
[SPEAKER_04]: It's just, you know, and I know we've been talking a lot about the $25 million in certified free cash that we learned about a couple months ago, which really should be good news, and it is good news in a way.

504
00:41:19,526 --> 00:41:33,013
[SPEAKER_04]: But, you know, what I really am having a hard time reconciling is, you know, that amount of available funding to fill needs in our community and, you know, $100,000 that would make a really big difference for our library now.

505
00:41:33,987 --> 00:41:35,408
[SPEAKER_04]: So it's really hard for me to comment.

506
00:41:35,428 --> 00:41:41,590
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think probably you'll hear, you know, what a priority for this council, the library is.

507
00:41:41,630 --> 00:41:44,911
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think that's because of the good work they're already doing in the community.

508
00:41:45,431 --> 00:41:45,631
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

509
00:41:48,786 --> 00:41:57,612
[SPEAKER_10]: I think the I think the best questions have probably been asked but I just, I wanted to reiterate and build upon some of the points that my fellow counselors are making.

510
00:41:58,033 --> 00:42:03,857
[SPEAKER_10]: It seems like we built a brand new library, right and we were all we're using that to patch over.

511
00:42:04,617 --> 00:42:12,220
[SPEAKER_10]: a lot of the funding problems that we're having and that were long existing before we built the new library, too.

512
00:42:12,761 --> 00:42:23,385
[SPEAKER_10]: And I think, I mean, it's symptomatic of what we often do here is we have something flashy that covers up the maintenance and the long-term planning aspect of things.

513
00:42:24,026 --> 00:42:33,350
[SPEAKER_10]: I think it's just such a shame that we're not fully funding such a beautiful resource and one that we're seeing so much demand for in our community.

514
00:42:35,451 --> 00:42:44,656
[SPEAKER_10]: And so I just wanted to throw my support behind all of you guys and thank you for the work that you're doing despite how understaffed you are.

515
00:42:44,676 --> 00:42:54,742
[SPEAKER_10]: I think residents should definitely know that there's no reason why our ordinary costs should be lower than 2017.

516
00:42:57,214 --> 00:42:58,995
[SPEAKER_10]: The dollar doesn't go as far anymore.

517
00:42:59,015 --> 00:43:00,817
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't think that's a secret to anyone.

518
00:43:02,038 --> 00:43:04,399
[SPEAKER_10]: And that it just puts more strain on you guys.

519
00:43:05,180 --> 00:43:07,101
[SPEAKER_10]: And the new building doesn't help with that, right?

520
00:43:07,221 --> 00:43:12,204
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, it's a great venue, but the bricks of the building don't give you guys the books.

521
00:43:12,264 --> 00:43:14,946
[SPEAKER_10]: That's not where the books and the eBooks come from.

522
00:43:15,747 --> 00:43:17,428
[SPEAKER_10]: And so I'm 100% behind you all.

523
00:43:20,450 --> 00:43:23,832
[SPEAKER_10]: whatever this council can do to help you get what you need.

524
00:43:24,433 --> 00:43:27,935
[SPEAKER_10]: I think we, all of us behind the rail are really committed to it.

525
00:43:28,315 --> 00:43:40,764
[SPEAKER_10]: And I personally have been bringing it up whenever I've been able to talk to the mayor and talk to other folks in the city to bring more, both bring more attention, but also to push for something substantive in terms of the dollar amounts that we're seeing in the budget.

526
00:43:40,804 --> 00:43:41,885
[SPEAKER_10]: And I am hopeful.

527
00:43:42,305 --> 00:43:45,827
[SPEAKER_10]: I think there have been open channels of communication about it.

528
00:43:46,008 --> 00:43:49,330
[SPEAKER_10]: And so I'm pretty hopeful that we can get something better for you all.

529
00:43:50,414 --> 00:44:02,096
[SPEAKER_06]: One of the things that I forgot to mention was last year there was a lot of concern because there wasn't any in the money in the budget for maintenance, but already has taken that over so that is actually well in hand this year.

530
00:44:03,327 --> 00:44:04,748
[SPEAKER_06]: And it's great.

531
00:44:04,768 --> 00:44:09,871
[SPEAKER_06]: I have no idea what to do on the roof so it's good.

