[SPEAKER_08]: I really hope that is the number that comes back to us for a number of reasons.

1408
02:07:06,738 --> 02:07:09,900
[SPEAKER_08]: I think most recent, you know, we all had that, that Welch report.

1409
02:07:09,960 --> 02:07:12,001
[SPEAKER_08]: And I think similar to the library where,

1410
02:07:12,475 --> 02:07:27,047
[SPEAKER_08]: you know, we're spending money, or the small amount of money, and then to not do the next thing, to not do, you know, we get this report that says here are all the things we need to do, and then hoping we have the funding to actually do those things, to understand that we're faced with challenges.

1411
02:07:27,447 --> 02:07:36,835
[SPEAKER_08]: We spent the money to find out what those challenges are, how we can address them, and then hoping we get the money from the administration to actually do those things and make the changes to really bring us to where we need to be.

1412
02:07:38,036 --> 02:07:41,759
[SPEAKER_08]: I think the report was heartening in a way, too, in that we face a lot of challenges

1413
02:07:42,404 --> 02:07:45,305
[SPEAKER_08]: a lot of other communities face, but we have them outlined now.

1414
02:07:45,405 --> 02:07:46,205
[SPEAKER_08]: So I appreciate that.

1415
02:07:46,245 --> 02:07:49,366
[SPEAKER_08]: That of course is a small part of this very large budget.

1416
02:07:49,606 --> 02:07:51,207
[SPEAKER_08]: I appreciate the highlights.

1417
02:07:51,227 --> 02:07:54,668
[SPEAKER_08]: That's really important as far as literacy programming and all of that, the arts.

1418
02:07:55,068 --> 02:07:56,229
[SPEAKER_08]: I thank you for calling that out.

1419
02:07:56,309 --> 02:08:02,091
[SPEAKER_08]: And I really want to see that, that fully funded and hope we can get there when we get that number before us on Tuesday night.

1420
02:08:02,171 --> 02:08:05,492
[SPEAKER_08]: So, and I appreciate your time as always and back to councilor Seng.

1421
02:08:05,793 --> 02:08:10,757
[SPEAKER_10]: Sorry, there was one point that I wanted to close on, and it just escaped me when I was speaking.

1422
02:08:11,138 --> 02:08:13,380
[SPEAKER_10]: But I was going to make the point.

1423
02:08:14,521 --> 02:08:19,625
[SPEAKER_10]: We've been talking a lot about the consequences of the pandemic, be it with mental health, safety, all of that.

1424
02:08:20,125 --> 02:08:32,116
[SPEAKER_10]: It might not be obvious on paper, but the missing positions that we would cut out if we don't get to that 71.9 are positions that would really directly

1425
02:08:33,677 --> 02:08:36,679
[SPEAKER_10]: to address all of those concerns, right?

1426
02:08:36,759 --> 02:08:51,946
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, I think the literary stuff is very self-explanatory, but when we look at the importance of converting libraries to the library staff or the theater teacher, all of those are ways in which we can tackle those concerns that a lot of parents have in the community as well.

1427
02:08:52,087 --> 02:08:58,210
[SPEAKER_10]: And that's, I think, a very compelling reason to support the 71.9 figure and to really work hard to get there.

1428
02:08:58,230 --> 02:09:00,131
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Councilor Saik.

1429
02:09:00,971 --> 02:09:02,332
