[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1457
02:11:29,166 --> 02:11:31,928
[SPEAKER_08]: Questions, discussion from the council on debt service bonds and interest?

1458
02:11:38,183 --> 02:11:38,963
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Madam President.

1459
02:11:38,983 --> 02:11:39,983
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Director Dickinson.

1460
02:11:40,003 --> 02:11:53,667
[SPEAKER_17]: I was looking at the DLS community comparison chart, and I pulled up just our neighbors, Winchester, Arlington, Somerville, Melrose, Everett, Stoneham, and Malden.

1461
02:11:54,227 --> 02:12:03,490
[SPEAKER_17]: We're the lowest of all of those communities, relatively significantly in the percentage of our annual operating budget that is general fund debt service.

1462
02:12:05,823 --> 02:12:17,457
[SPEAKER_17]: I have thoughts that, you know, that makes me think we could maybe, and I'm pretty sure the CIP keeps us at about a 3% target, if that's correct, but.

1463
02:12:18,278 --> 02:12:23,064
[SPEAKER_13]: Well, respectfully, wait until you try to build a new high school.

1464
02:12:23,825 --> 02:12:25,027
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, exactly.

1465
02:12:25,593 --> 02:12:27,815
[SPEAKER_13]: So, I mean, we have to look at that down the road.

1466
02:12:29,416 --> 02:12:47,510
[SPEAKER_13]: Yeah, you know, compared to my former employer, that's a very, very simple debt schedule and there isn't a lot of debt out there actually, quite frankly, but it's a very, it was a very different place in terms of what we had to fund, so.

1467
02:12:48,790 --> 02:12:54,395
[SPEAKER_13]: But yeah, there's not a great deal of debt burden on Medford right now.

1468
02:12:55,290 --> 02:12:55,510
[SPEAKER_17]: Right.

1469
02:12:57,232 --> 02:12:58,453
[SPEAKER_13]: You gotta pay for it, so.

1470
02:12:59,594 --> 02:12:59,774
[SPEAKER_17]: Right.

1471
02:12:59,914 --> 02:13:02,776
[SPEAKER_17]: No, and that's, you know, that's the positive side of it.

1472
02:13:02,876 --> 02:13:09,181
[SPEAKER_17]: You know, my feeling is like, does that also mean there's capital needs that could be funded through debt service that we're maybe not funding?

1473
02:13:09,762 --> 02:13:15,887
[SPEAKER_17]: If we were to do a debt exclusion for a new high school, would that count towards the general fund debt service or would that be outside of it?

1474
02:13:16,695 --> 02:13:26,023
[SPEAKER_13]: It would be general fund debt service, but because it would be a debt override, we'd simply add it to the tax rate.

1475
02:13:26,043 --> 02:13:28,506
[SPEAKER_13]: It would be added to the tax rate.

1476
02:13:28,566 --> 02:13:31,388
[SPEAKER_13]: We'd simply tax more in order to pay that specific debt.

1477
02:13:32,209 --> 02:13:46,099
[SPEAKER_13]: But when you think about the tax rate, a 30-year debt, I think I did this the other day, a 30-year debt at 5% on $200 million, you're talking about $13 million a year.

1478
02:13:46,940 --> 02:13:56,707
[SPEAKER_13]: That's 10% of what we're taking in terms of what we're charging in real estate and personal property tax right now.

1479
02:13:57,687 --> 02:13:59,148
[SPEAKER_13]: So taxes would go up 10%.

1480
02:14:00,409 --> 02:14:15,307
[SPEAKER_13]: Right right right to fund that so yeah we you yes an override would be paid for outside of the general fund budget essentially it would be tacked onto the property taxes.

1481
02:14:15,791 --> 02:14:20,874
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, I'm just really glad that my, probably much less scientific than your estimate was about 12 million.

1482
02:14:20,894 --> 02:14:21,755
[SPEAKER_17]: So I was pretty close.

1483
02:14:22,215 --> 02:14:28,720
[SPEAKER_13]: Um, and again, that's, that's running, of course, in interest rates have been very volatile.

1484
02:14:28,780 --> 02:14:36,465
[SPEAKER_13]: That's one of the reasons we have a hundred thousand dollars set aside for short term interest rates right now, because they're much higher than they were last year.

1485
02:14:36,725 --> 02:14:38,026
[SPEAKER_13]: So, okay.

1486
02:14:38,926 --> 02:14:42,429
[SPEAKER_17]: So, so when I'm looking at this and I'm seeing Winchester at like eight, 8% of their

1487
02:14:43,299 --> 02:14:50,926
[SPEAKER_17]: operating budget, Arlington, Somerville at 6%, that's because they've done overrides, debt exclusions for construction projects.

1488
02:14:51,066 --> 02:14:52,007
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, I know they all have.

1489
02:14:52,067 --> 02:14:58,552
[SPEAKER_13]: It may be and it, you know, it has, just to give you an example, I mean Nantucket

1490
02:14:59,833 --> 02:15:09,516
[SPEAKER_13]: which I'm familiar with has, I wanna say, $100 million out there in sewer debt alone.

1491
02:15:10,197 --> 02:15:14,338
[SPEAKER_13]: But that's because Nantucket is an island that has sewer treatment plants, two of them.

1492
02:15:15,393 --> 02:15:17,895
[SPEAKER_13]: they're enormously expensive.

1493
02:15:18,276 --> 02:15:20,918
[SPEAKER_13]: So there was a need to do that.

1494
02:15:21,779 --> 02:15:22,940
[SPEAKER_13]: There was no way around it.

1495
02:15:24,101 --> 02:15:35,532
[SPEAKER_13]: To actually compare surrounding communities' debt, you'd have to look at it at a more granular level to see exactly what they use the debt for.

1496
02:15:35,692 --> 02:15:38,554
[SPEAKER_17]: Cool, well, that's helpful.

1497
02:15:38,574 --> 02:15:40,096
[SPEAKER_17]: Because I was looking at this and I was just saying,

1498
02:15:41,387 --> 02:15:46,528
[SPEAKER_17]: is this, is this a, are we an outlier or is there a specific reason that we're so much lower?

1499
02:15:46,548 --> 02:15:58,651
[SPEAKER_17]: And it seems to me at least knowing, you know, that Winchester Arlington and Somerville have done large debt exclusions for capital projects relatively recently, that would explain the difference to me.

1500
02:15:58,751 --> 02:16:00,452
[SPEAKER_17]: So great.

1501
02:16:00,552 --> 02:16:00,912
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

